<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-115-256  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 115 256.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  April 1989 v9 n4 p18(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The iron horse enters the space age: railroads embrace hightechnology to get back on track with better service and higherprofits.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pope, Gregory T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Railroads are investing in high-technology control andcommunications systems to boost efficiency and put moreinformation in the hands of top management.andP;  Systems include suchfeatures as mobile data links, computer-controlled heavymachinery, radio transponders, remote equipment diagnostics, andsatellite communication.andP;  Leading the automation effort is theAdvanced Train Control System (ATCS), an industry-wide set ofperformance specifications developed for both US and Canadian railtrade associations by ARINC Research Corp, which also developedsystem specifications for the airlines industry.andP;  ATCS is amodular system which railroads can phase in over their own timeframe.andP;  ATCs offers automatic monitoring and control of traintraffic as well as more efficient use of fuel and track capacityand better safety.andP;  Several railroads are testing ATCS or similarautomation systems and several vendors supply equipment.andP;  Onesource estimates payback time at five years.andP;  Eventually, ATCS cantie into such other automated systems as electronic datainterchange and automated train-car identification.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Railroad IndustryAutomationApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   ATCS relies on trackbed transponders, transmits via a 900-MHzradio link. (chart)ARES receives satellite signals, transmits data over standard VHFsignal. (chart)Railstar takes ground-based transmitter signals, transmits viasatellite. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>